== STEP 1: Clarifying Questions ==

Functional Requirements:
1) Do users need to login to use our application ?
   -> No, login is optional. Anonymous pastes allowed. Logged-in users can manage/delete their pastes.

2) Is there any expiration time for a paste ?
   -> Yes. Users can set: 1 hour, 1 day, 1 week, 1 month, or never (default: never).

3) What is the max size of a paste ?
   -> 1 MB of plain text.

4) Are custom URLs allowed ?
   -> Nice to have, not required for v1.

5) Do we need analytics (e.g. view count) ?
   -> Basic analytics — just view count per paste.

Non-Functional Requirements:
6) How many active users are we expecting in a day ?
   -> ~1 million DAU. ~5 million paste writes/day, ~25 million reads/day.

7) What is the read to write ratio ?
   -> 5:1 — system is read-heavy.

8) Should the system be globally available ?
   -> Yes, global users — low latency reads (~100ms) are important.

9) What are the availability and durability expectations ?
   -> High availability (reads must never go down). No data loss (durable storage).


== STEP 2: Capacity Estimation ==

Write QPS (new pastes):
5,000,000 writes/day / (24 * 3600) = 5,000,000 / 86,400 = ~58 QPS
[Note: used 5M writes/day not 1M DAU — not every user writes a paste every day]

Read QPS:
25,000,000 reads/day / (24 * 3600) = 25,000,000 / 86,400 = ~290 QPS


Storage per paste (use AVERAGE size, not max):
userId   : 8 bytes
content  : ~10 KB avg  [Correction: max is 1 MB but avg snippet is small; always use avg]
metadata : ~500 bytes (paste_id, expiry, created_at, title, etc.)
Total    : ~10.5 KB per paste ≈ ~10 KB

1 year storage:
10 KB * 5,000,000 writes/day * 365 days = ~18.25 TB/year

5 year storage:
18.25 TB * 5 = ~91.25 TB


