== Step 4: High-Level Architecture ==

Client  -> CDN -> LoadBalancer  ->     (Application Layer) ->   Redis      -> DataBase
                                        PasteBin Service                    Metadata (user_id, paste_id, expiry, created_at)        
                                        Key Generation Service              Content (paste_id, content) ()

Scheduled Job (Run once a day)
- Cleanup expired pastes
- Archive old pastes

Flow:
Client - sends request to CDN
If data is in CDN return the reesponse from there for reads, for post, go to loadbalancer
Else
CDN - forwards to LoadBalancer
LoadBalancer - distributes request to Application Layer (acts as a rate limitter also)
Application Layer - processes request
PasteBinService - generates paste_id, checks if paste is expired, returns content
Redis - key (paste_bin, content) with TTL : 24 hours If not there, interrats with database, write back to redis (cache-aside pattern)
DataBase - metadata - is a noemal DataBas
cONTENT is a storage database (S3, GCS) - MORE HElpful than storing blobs in relation database, faster


 === Step 5: Deep Dives ===

 1) database
    SQL/NO SQL
    ----------
    1) Metadata DB - has a fixed  rigid structure
    - structure doesnt change over time
    - queries on this table first always (complex joins or quesries in future)
    So going forward with SQL
    index : paste_id, expiry_date
    primary_key: paste_id

    (title: varchar(255) ,
    user_id: varchar(255)(FK Point to Users table) 
    paste_id: varchar(6) (NOT NULL) (Point to S3) 
    expiry_date: date_time,
     s3_url: varchar(255
    created_at: date_time(NOT NULL),)

Content DB
- storage heavy
- relation database BLOB will need expontential inceease in future
- using S3/GCS for storage 
- object storage kind of database


2) Unique Key Generation
    1) UUID 
        - less chance of collision
        - unique ID always
        - ll be random and nonsequential
        - but is very long in length (32 chars), we need something small

    2) Auto increment (with some fixed length)
        - use a counter to generate unique IDs
        - but is very long in length, we need something small
        - in case 2 servers are there, collision will happen when they are trying to write
        - can be useful if the application is small overall

    3) Hashing + Encoding (Deterministic)
     - Create a hash using SHA-256, MD5 etc and encode it to base62 or base36
     - encoding will reduce the length of the hash
     - In case collision happen - add some salt then rehash again
     - difficult to decipher the next

    4) KGS (Pre-generated Keys)
   - Pre-generate millions of random Base62 keys offline
   - Store in a DB: unused_keys table + used_keys table
   - On paste creation, app calls KGS → gets a key → marks it used
   - No collision possible (key is claimed before use)
   - Fast (no hashing at request time)
   - Downside: KGS is a SPOF → mitigate with 2 KGS instances + each caches a batch of keys in memory

   Will choose 4 for our usecase


